me to address queerness, disability and biopolitics togetherThis book examines why Beckett’s writing is so queer, so disabled and disabling. Why did Beckett write so often about mental illness, disability, perversion? Why did he take such an interest in ‘abnormals’ and ‘degenerates’? How did he reconceive ‘the human’ in the wake of Hitler and Stalin? Drawing on Beckett’s voluminous archive, as well as his primary texts, the authors use psychoanalysis, queer theory, disability theory and biopolitics to push Beckett studies beyond the normal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBiopolitics in literature. 0aDisabilities in literature. 0aSexual orientation in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aBarilar, Nic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrophy, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeffer, Byron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Seán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aValente, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalker, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311078041340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147446048440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474460484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474460484/original  a978-3-11-078041-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  a